Human hair extensions <p></p></span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-864_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-866_">Step One: Preparation</span></h3><div title="Human Hair Loc Extensions " data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-GEbAx gWfVlz pf-867_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0069/6470/7389/t/9/assets/pf-2e642ad3--Blog-August-Images-3.jpg?v=1596734518" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0069/6470/7389/t/9/assets/pf-2e642ad3--Blog-August-Images-3.jpg?v=1596734518 1536w" width="500" height="545" alt="Cliphair loc Extensions" title="Human Hair Loc Extensions "/></div><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-868_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-870_">Take a small section of your hair extensions, (choose amount of hair according to how thick you want your dreadlocks to be). Once you decide how thick you want the dreadlocks, cut the extensions at the wefts and continue to get as many pieces as you like for your dreads. Hold each hair piece with a plastic hair band.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-76b6" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-hAcGzb jHOovW pf-871_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-eGPXGI cIlovf"><div class="sc-iCfMLu eehqFj pf-872_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-XxNYO eWQzGj pf-873_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-874_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-876_">Step Two: Backcomb</span></h3><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-877_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-879_">Place the piece of hair somewhere sturdy, use a hair extensions holder or a clipper to hold the hair. Hold the hair in a 45-degree angle and begin to back comb about three inches, pushing the hair back. <p></p>
Once you’ve done the initial backcombing, you’ll need to go back to that area and backcomb the hair again about one inch deep. The tighter you backcomb the hair, the denser your human hair loc extensions will be and they’ll also have shape. Once you get to end of that hair, break it up and smooth it a little bit and backcomb it again. Take turns in twisting and backcombing the hair.</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-880_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-882_">Step Three: Roll, roll, roll</span></h3><div title="weave weft human hair dreadlocks" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-GEbAx gWfVlz pf-883_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0069/6470/7389/t/9/assets/pf-482e642a--Blog-August-Images-2.jpg?v=1596734509" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0069/6470/7389/t/9/assets/pf-482e642a--Blog-August-Images-2.jpg?v=1596734509 1536w" width="500" height="550" alt="Weave weft dreadlocks" title="weave weft human hair dreadlocks"/></div></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-XxNYO eWQzGj pf-884_"><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-885_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-887_">Once your human hair loc extension piece is tight from the backcombing, begin to roll. To get the best results, concentrate on one area at a time. The key to getting the perfect, tight dreadlock is down to heat, friction, and concentration on one area at a time so make sure you feel the hair getting warmer and tighter. <p> </p>
